[The indigenous peoples in the Yanomami communities are particularly at risk of contracting measles because of their low resistance to diseases that are introduced from outsiders. There are approximately 35 000 Yanomami remaining alive. The Yanomami lived in relative isolation until recently, and consequently are na√Øve to most diseases encountered in Brazil. It is difficult to reach them in the tropical rain forest of Southern Venezuela and Northern Brazil, where they live. But according to a 5 Jul 2018 report from CNN, the Brazilian MoH said medical teams have been deployed to the region as well as 711 400 doses of the MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccine. One has to hope the community will be receptive to receiving the vaccine. - Mod.LK

