******
[2] USA (South Carolina, Georgetown County)
Date: Fri 10 Aug 2018
Source: Myrtle Beach Online [edited]
https://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/news/local/article216498810.html


The 1st case of measles in South Carolina since 1997 has been reported in Georgetown County, according to the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control. DHEC says it received a report on Fri [10 Aug 2018] of a confirmed case of measles in a resident who lives in Georgetown County. The state agency is investigating and trying to contact people who may have been exposed. DHEC said that it has instructed healthcare providers to look for patients with symptoms of measles and immediately report cases to their regional public health office.

According to DHEC, measles was declared eliminated in the US in 2000 but is still common in parts of the world. DHEC says this is the 2nd confirmed case of measles in South Carolina since 1990, with the last case being found in Charleston in 1997.

"Measles is an acute viral respiratory illness and is highly contagious," said Dr Linda Bell, DHEC's state epidemiologist, in a news release. "It is critical that healthcare providers and the public be aware of the symptoms associated with this disease. The best way to prevent measles is by vaccination. I strongly encourage everyone to review their immunization records and make sure there are no other immunizations you need." ...

[byline: Christian Boschult]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This case was most likely travel-associated, either through the patient having been exposed during travel or by being exposed to an infected individual from another country. Either way, the individual would not have been vaccinated and, therefore, was susceptible. See below for cases in Michigan, with similar risk and exposure. - Mod.LK

HealthMap, South Carolina, USA: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5961680,242]

