[4] Ireland (Dublin)
Date: Fri 10 Aug 2018
Source: The Journal [edited]
http://www.thejournal.ie/measles-dublin-3-4172774-Aug2018/


The Health Service Executive (HSE) has been notified of a further 5 cases of measles in Dublin, bringing the total number of cases in recent weeks to 11. A spokesperson for the HSE said that the organisation is "particularly concerned" about the risk of measles in children who attended Temple Street Children's University Hospital on certain dates in July and August 2018 and "may have been exposed to an infectious case of measles".

Earlier this month [August 2018], it was confirmed that 2 adults and 2 children were likely to have developed measles from contact with one of the 2 earlier cases at hospitals in Dublin. If an adult or child attended Temple Street Hospital on any of these dates and develops symptoms of measles, they have been advised to stay at home and phone their general practitioner for advice.

People at increased risk of getting measles are those who are not fully vaccinated with 2 doses of MMR vaccine or who have not had measles in the past. ...

There are ongoing outbreaks of measles in multiple countries in Europe and worldwide. Most of the cases in the EU in 2018 were reported from Romania, France, Greece and Italy. Most people who get measles on holiday do not know they were exposed until they develop disease, the HSE said. Unrecognised exposures to measles have occurred at airports, on planes, at concerts, in shops, and in healthcare settings. In 2018, 31 deaths associated with measles have been reported in EU countries.

Vaccination remains the most effective measure against infection. Children aged 6-11 months who are travelling to other countries and regions where measles outbreaks have been reported are recommended to get the MMR vaccine. A dose given before 12 months of age does not replace the dose that would normally be given at 12 months of age, the HSE advised.

Older children should be age-appropriately vaccinated. Children who have missed their recommended doses should get the MMR vaccine from their GP. Adults may be at risk of measles, particularly those under 40 years of age who have never had measles or 2 doses of a measles vaccine.

